"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350073","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 15 June 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-10/1927/" target="_blank">1927</a></p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","2221 ; 2222 ; 2223 ; 2225","2015-06-16T12:46:59.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350073/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350073/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-11","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if he will include in his proposals on English votes for English laws details of the proposed process of certification for a piece of legislation as English-only.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","2220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350074","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 15 June 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-10/1927/" target="_blank">1927</a></p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","2220 ; 2221 ; 2222 ; 2223","2015-06-16T12:46:59.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350074/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350074/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-11","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if he will include in his proposals on English votes for English laws an assessment of the potential opportunities for legal challenge to a decision that a particular piece of legislation is England-only.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","2225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350075","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>Sodium valproate was licensed in the United Kingdom in 1972 as a treatment for epilepsy and was marketed in 1974 for general prescription. The risks known to be associated with sodium valproate at that time were described in the data sheet first published in 1975 in the Association of British Pharmaceutical Industry (ABPI) Data Sheet Compendium. A copy is attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The safety of sodium valproate was monitored after licensing using data from the Yellow Card Scheme, which was set up in 1964 to collect reports of suspected adverse reactions to medicines. The data sheet published in the 1980-81 ABPI Data Sheet Compendium reflects the safety profile of sodium valproate following five years of availability on general prescription. A copy is attached.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-19T10:52:15.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350075/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350075/answer","Epilim datasheet 1975.pdf ; Epilim datasheet 1980-81.pdf","Epilim datasheet 1975.pdf ; Epilim datasheet 1980-81.pdf","ABPI Datasheet for Epilim - 1975 ; ABPI Datasheet for Epilim - 1980-81","ABPI Datasheet for Epilim - 1975 ; ABPI Datasheet for Epilim - 1980-81","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350075/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","Sodium Valproate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information he holds on what knowledge his Department had of the emergence of risks associated with sodium valproate within the first five years following first prescription of that drug.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","2077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350076","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-16","<p /> <p>We will publish a full Impact Assessment in due course.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-16T13:20:29.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350076/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350076/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-11","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many homeless households living in temporary accommodation would be affected by the reduction of the benefit cap to £23,000 per annum if management fees were exempted from calculation of income from benefits.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","2142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350077","Home Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The medical implications of Taser use are independently assessed by the Scientific Advisory Committee on the Medical Implications of Less-Lethal weapons (SACMILL) SACMILL’s latest statement can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2012-0729/96605%20Library%20Deposit.pdf" target="_blank">http://data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2012-0729/96605%20Library%20Deposit.pdf</a></p><p>The police Authorised Professional Practice on Taser makes clear that before specially trained officers use Taser, there are a number of factors to be considered. These include whether there are any pre-existing medical conditions. The APP also states that all persons who have been subjected to the discharge of a Taser should be examined by a Forensic Medical Examiner (FME) as soon as practicable. Where officers believe that a person to whom a Taser has been applied has a cardiac pacemaker, other implanted device or pre-existing medical condition, an immediate referral should be made to hospital.</p><p>The guidance can be found at: <a href="https://www.app.college.police.uk/app-content/armed-policing/conducted-energy-devices-taser/" target="_blank">https://www.app.college.police.uk/app-content/armed-policing/conducted-energy-devices-taser/</a></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-16T15:25:21.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350077/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350077/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-11","Stun Guns: Medical Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the risks to people fitted with medical electronic devices of the use by police of tasers; and what steps she has taken to mitigate those risks.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","2120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350078","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-19","<p>The government is committed to providing an inclusive service through Pension Wise and is working with its delivery partners to ensure accessibility of pension guidance across the UK. Telephone appointments are delivered by the Pension Advisory Service and can be accessed in any part of the UK through free, outbound telephone calls. Face-to-face appointments are delivered by over 500 Citizens Advice bureau locations, two of which are in Bristol, on Quay Street and Broad Street. The Hon. Lady is welcome to arrange a visit.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-19T13:24:59.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350078/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350078/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-11","Pensions: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will ensure that a Pensions Wise advice service is made available in the City of Bristol.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","2285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350079","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-16","<p /> <p>The Government has not made an assessment of the potential merits of rolling the value of pensioner benefits into the state pension. Means tested, disability, care and universal benefits serve different purposes alongside the state pension.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-16T16:32:51.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350079/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350079/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-11","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of rolling the value of pensioner benefits into the state pension.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","2286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350080","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-16","<p /> <p>As part of our Jobcentre modernisation programme we have replaced all Customer Access Telephones with computers. Alongside this we provide an assisted service for claimants who require additional support while using the computers.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants who require access to a telephone in connection with their benefit or job search will still be given access to a telephone in a Jobcentre.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-16T11:48:32.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350080/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350080/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-11","Jobcentres: Telephones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will ensure that all jobcentres provide access to telephones for jobseekers to apply for jobs when no computer is required or the jobseeker is unable to use a computer.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","2287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350081","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-18","<p>Defra officials attended the launch of the document on 3 June 2015. The report will be considered in the context of the ongoing 5 year review of the Welfare of Racing Greyhounds Regulations 2010 on which Defra plans to consult later this year.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-18T13:39:31.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350081/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350081/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-11","Greyhounds: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the implications for its policies of the findings of the report, The Greyhound Industry: Don't bet on fair treatment, published by the Dogs Trust on 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","2084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350082","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-18","<p>The UK was the fastest growing G7 economy in 2014 and the OECD forecasts that we will be so again in 2015. At the same time, UK income inequality is lower than it was in 2010-11 and living standards are forecast to be higher than they have ever been this year.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-18T11:49:17.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350082/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-11","Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of economic inequalities on growth.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350083","Department of Health","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Government is committed to supporting the National Health Service to provide safe, high quality, sustainable care that provides patients with the care they need and maximises value for money for taxpayers. The Government and its arm’s length bodies are therefore working with NHS organisations to ensure that patient care is safe, high quality and financially sustainable and that swift action is taken when there are significant failings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Francis Report and other reports on the quality of care, which highlighted the problems of short-staffing in some parts of the NHS, were followed by increased recruitment, including temporary staff from agencies. We are taking action to ensure that the focus going forward is on employing permanent staff and on making staffing decisions in the most cost effective way to ensure that NHS organisations are providing high care, safe care while living within their budgets.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-18T14:49:50Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350083/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350083/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","NHS Trusts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of financial deficits of NHS trusts on safety and quality of care.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350084","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>Information is not held centrally on the number of people in England who are involuntarily addicted to prescribed drugs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information is not held centrally on the number of people prescribed particular medicines or the duration of treatment.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","2082","2015-06-19T10:49:14.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350084/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350084/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the number of people in England involuntarily addicted to prescribed drugs in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350085","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer of the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) on 1 June 2015 (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-05-27/292/" target="_blank">PQ 292</a>).</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-06-16T13:44:12.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350085/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350085/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-11","Burma: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on the situation in Rakine State, Burma.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350086","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>We remain deeply concerned by the dire living conditions facing the Rohingya people in Rakhine State, which is leading thousands to flee by sea to other countries in the region. It is vital that Burma addresses the longer-term issues which lie at the root of the problem, including the persecution of the Rohingya. The UK is playing its part to resolve the situation in Rakhine State. Since 2012, the UK has been one of the largest bilateral humanitarian donors in Rakhine State, contributing over £18m in humanitarian aid there. We will continue raise the underlying political problems and human rights abuses both bilaterally and in international fora.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-06-16T15:54:44.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350086/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350086/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-11","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure the human rights of the Rohingya people in Burma are protected.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350087","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>Information is not held centrally on the number of people in England who are involuntarily addicted to prescribed drugs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information is not held centrally on the number of people prescribed particular medicines or the duration of treatment.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","2081","2015-06-19T10:49:14.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350087/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350087/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","Prescription Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people in England who have been prescribed benzodiazepines and z drugs for longer than four weeks in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350088","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-16","<p /> <p> </p><p>The Court rejected two of the three legal grounds brought by the claimants, finding that their human rights had not been breached and not awarding damages.</p><p> </p><p>Where the Court found that the historic delay for the two claimants was unlawful, they also ruled that they are not “test cases” and it would be inappropriate to make wider findings.</p><p> </p><p>The Court accepted that the Government had made significant improvements to the Personal Independence Payment process and there are now no inherent failings in the system.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of these improvements, the average time taken for a claimant to be assessed by an assessment provider has more than halved since June 2014. In March 2015, the average claimant wait was 7 weeks for their PIP assessment - well within the 16 week target set by the Secretary of State.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-16T13:49:24.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350088/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350088/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-11","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the implications for his Department's policies are of the ruling in the case of Ms C and Mr W v. Secretary of State for Work and Pensions and others of 8 June 2015.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350089","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Government takes the firm view that consumers must be able to access clear and transparent information about their accounts with banks and other financial service companies, utility companies, media companies and other service companies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>With regards to banking, for example, the Government is continuing to drive forward a wide-reaching and ambitious programme of reforms to open up competition in the banking sector, including enabling innovation in the use of bank data so that customers are able to use online information more effectively. This includes initiatives like the Midata current account tool, which will help customers switch to the best current account for them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority is also currently reviewing cost-cutting initiatives that affect a significant number of customers, including the withdrawal of paper statements.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-22T16:38:14.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350089/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350089/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-11","Consumers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will respond formally to the Keep Me Posted campaign.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","2141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350090","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-16","<p>The A400M Atlas transport aircraft is being procured as part of a European collaborative programme, and its certification basis is explicitly defined in the multinational acquisition contract.</p><p>The A400M Atlas' certification basis is drawn principally from recognised civil standards, with additional military certification as necessary for any specific military capabilities. The certification basis is overseen by the European Aviation Safety Agency, and is in accordance with established international airworthiness standards. The European Aviation Safety Agency has granted Type Certificates for the A400M aircraft type, engine and propeller.</p><p>To obtain these Type Certificates, Airbus Defence and Space (the A400M Atlas Design Authority) had to present appropriate evidence for validation and approval by the European Aviation Safety Agency. In addition, certification evidence is also reviewed by an independent certification and qualification organisation established by the partner nations to provide an additional level of military certification expertise.</p><p>A400M Atlas is already subject to a rigorous, independent certification process that has been accepted by all participating nations, and that is conducted by a competent European regulatory body with significant lineage in the certification of all Airbus aircraft products. They will review certification requirements and the associated evidence when there is new information to consider. Consequently, there are currently no plans to review this.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-16T15:04:55.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350090/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350090/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-11","Future Large Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department plans to take to review the airworthiness certification regime of the A400m programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350091","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-16","<p>The investigation by Spanish judicial and air accident investigation authorities into the A400M crash on 9 May 2015 is ongoing, and it would not be appropriate to make any comment prior to its conclusion.</p><p>Once complete, the outcome of that investigation will be reviewed to determine whether any further action is considered necessary.</p><p>Immediately after the crash the Ministry of Defence (MOD) temporarily paused flying its two A400M aircraft until more was known about the crash. I can confirm that the MOD is content that it now understands the likely cause of the crash and has put in place procedures to allow a safe return to flight and, as a consequence, UK A400M aircraft were cleared to return to flight on 15 June 2015.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-16T15:04:17.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350091/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350091/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-11","Future Large Aircraft: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if his Department will prepare and publish a report on the causes of the recent crash of an A400m aircraft in Spain after the Spanish authorities have concluded their investigations.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350092","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-16","<p>The Military Aviation Authority (MAA) was established in response to the recommendations made by Mr Justice Haddon-Cave in his Nimrod Review, which called for a radical overhaul of Military Air Safety regulation.</p><p>During 10-21 November 2014 an external audit team examined the MAA looking at its effectiveness as a regulator. MAA External Audit Panel 2014 (MEAP 14) assessed that the MAA is an effective air safety regulatory body, fit for purpose in its current role, with the opportunity to improve further as it continues to develop. MEAP 14 was satisfied that the remaining Nimrod Review recommendations have been implemented as intended, and that risks identified in previous audits have been addressed.</p><p> </p><p>The establishment of the MAA as an independent regulator has transformed the Department's approach to military air safety governance, with a focus on mitigating Risk to Life through the establishment of the aviation Duty Holder construct; the publication of concise, unambiguous and readily accessible regulations; a new regime for safety cases, aircraft type certification and release to service; and the establishment of an independent air accident investigation branch which has so far investigated 21 air safety occurrences and made over 460 recommendations to improve air safety.</p><p>MEAP 14 is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/search?q=MEAP+14" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/search?q=MEAP+14</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-16T15:06:17.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350092/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350092/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-11","Afghanistan: Nimrod Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the implication for his Department's proposals of the conclusions of the review into the broader issues surrounding the loss of the RAF Nimrod MR2 aircraft XV230 in Afghanistan in 2006 by Charles Haddon-Cave.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350093","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-16","<p>The Department is continuing to develop its response to the Law Commission’s recommendations on the reform of level crossing legislation in conjunction with stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>Our Level Crossing Reform Action Plan, copies of which are available in the House library, explains the steps that we are taking and includes an indicative timetable for completion of this process.</p><p> </p><p>The Action Plan notes that we expect to consult on proposals in those areas where we believe further policy and legal investigation was required during the summer.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-16T12:52:11.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350093/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350093/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-11","Level Crossings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress he has made in consulting stakeholders on reform of level crossing legislation; and if he will issue a public consultation on that matter.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","2215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350094","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>The £250 million funding for the building and equipping of the proton beam therapy centres at the Christie Hospital in Manchester and University College Hospital London is being funded by the Department and not NHS England.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-19T12:22:02.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350094/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350094/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","Radiotherapy: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answers of 17 March 2015 to Questions 227042 and 227043, from which budget NHS England will allocate funding for the building of the proton beam centres at the Christie Hospital in Manchester and University College Hospital London; and what contingency arrangements are in place for the planned budget being exceeded.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350095","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>On 15 June 2015, NHS England announced that the Newcastle upon Tyne Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and the South Tees Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust are among 17 centres across the country to begin to treat patients with stereotactic ablative radiotherapy (SABR), as part of a £15 million investment to assess the use of SABR.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Newcastle upon Tyne Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and South Tees Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust will be among the first centres to treat patients with SABR.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Source</em>: The Health and Social Care Information Centre, Hospital Episodes Statistics database 2013-14.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Notes: </em></p><p> </p><p>1. 2013-14 is the latest data available.</p><p> </p><p>2. Return is based on using the codes supplied by the classifications service (A10.7 Stereotactic radiosurgery on tissue of the brain and Y91.5 Megavoltage treatment for hypofractioned stereotactic radiotherapy).</p><p> </p><p>3. There are no specific OPCS-4.7 codes that classify stereotactic ablative radiotherapy. The terms stereotactic radiosurgery and stereotactic radiotherapy are sometimes used synonymously.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-19T10:42:50.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350095/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350095/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","Radiotherapy: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which hospitals in the North East are treating patients with (a) stereotactic radiosurgery (b) stereotactic ablative radiotherapy; and how many patients have been treated in both categories since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350096","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>Outstanding Government debt on the Severn Crossings, also known as the accumulated deficit, was £102m at 31 March 2014. Our forecast is that by the end of the concession period, expected in 2018, this will fall to £88m.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T13:20:52.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350096/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350096/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-11","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the amount of outstanding Government debt is on the Severn bridges.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","2244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350097","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-19","<p>HMRC have a statutory duty of confidentiality which limits the information they can disclose, including to Ministers.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-19T13:07:27.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350097/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350097/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-11","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much money the Exchequer received in VAT receipts from the Severn bridges between 2003 and 2014.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","2247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350098","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Severn River Crossings concession is expected to end in the first half of 2018. At the end of the concession, the Severn Crossings will revert to public ownership.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T13:14:08.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350098/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350098/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-11","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Severn bridges will revert to public ownership.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","2248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350099","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>Under the terms of the concession, Severn River Crossings Ltd (SRC) are compensated for changes in the tax regime. Under an agreement signed in 2012, the amount that SRC can collect in tolls was increased by £24.7m (July 1989 prices) to reflect the abolition of industrial building allowance on the Severn bridges; this is the additional amount of tax revenue from SRC resulting from this change.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T12:11:47.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350099/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350099/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-11","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of savings to the public purse from the abolition of the industrial buildings allowance on the Severn Bridges.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","2191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350100","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-17","<p>We are fully committed to complying with EU air quality standards as soon as possible. We have already committed over £2 billion since 2011 in transport measures to improve air quality and will be publishing revised air quality plans for nitrogen dioxide (NO<sub>2</sub>) by the end of this year. The plans will set out actions at all levels, including national and local, to achieve compliance with legal limits for NO<sub>2</sub> in the shortest possible time.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","2153","2015-06-17T08:34:35.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350100/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350100/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-11","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to tackle dangerous levels of air pollution in towns and cities.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","2122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350101","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-16","<p>The UK welcomes high quality overseas investment in the UK and the safe and economic development of nuclear power. It is the responsibility of the developers of new nuclear power stations to source components for the plant, in line with the UK’s robust nuclear regulatory regime. This regime requires the highest standards in safety and security to be met by developers and their technology providers. Quality assurance of all components for a nuclear power station are included within this regime.</p><p>The Government has made its policy clear in discussion with developers, that UK content to the supply chain should be maximised and is hence working closely with them to identify further UK opportunities in support of this. The Government also has supplier development and improvement programmes (Manufacturing Advisory Service (MAS) and Fit for Nuclear (F4N)) in place to help the UK supply chain better position itself to bid for these opportunities.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","1888","2015-06-16T11:19:13.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350101/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350101/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-11","Nuclear Power Stations: Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the benefits of ensuring that any deal with foreign investors on the funding of new nuclear power stations is independent from the manufacture and supply of the components required to build that infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","2131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>We deplore all incitement to violence and raise cases of concern with both the Palestinian and Israeli authorities as required. We have urged the leadership of both the Palestinian and Israeli authorities to avoid engaging in, or encouraging, the type of action and language which will make it more difficult to achieve a peaceful negotiated solution to the conflict. The issue of incitement was last raised with the Palestinian Authority in November 2014, due to our concerns over the volatile situation in Jerusalem and to the complaints we had received about a specific letter written by President Abbas. We continue to support Palestinian calls to reinstate the Tripartite Committee as the appropriate channel to deal with allegations of Palestinian or Israeli incitement.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T15:39:27.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350102/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-11","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Palestinian counterparts on the levels of incitement to violence against Israel.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","2277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350103","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-16","<p>The length of the land perimeter of the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area, excluding the small Republic of Cyprus enclaves, with (1) is approximately 50.4 km and (2) approximately 34.6 km. The Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area is also on the perimeter of the UN controlled zone and the length of the boundaries is approximately 8.5 km in the West and 1.1 km in the East.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-06-16T15:49:10.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350103/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350103/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-11","Cyprus","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the length of the land perimeter of the Sovereign Base Area of Dhekelia with (1) the area administered by the Turkish Cypriot Authorities, and (2) the area administered by the government of Cyprus.","false","Biography information for Lord Kilclooney",,"Lord Kilclooney","HL417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350104","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-25","<p>The UK has committed £427m to combat Ebola in West Africa, £373m for the ongoing response and £54m for early recovery programmes. This package of support covers the cost of UK operations, including Ministry of Defence assets and personnel, PHE clinicians, materials and medicines. Over £260 million has now been disbursed.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-06-25T16:39:51.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350104/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350104/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-11","West Africa: Ebola","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what has been the total cost so far of providing personnel from the Ministry of Defence, National Health Service and Public Health England, and materials and medicines from the United Kingdom, to international efforts to tackle the recent ebola crisis.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350105","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-18","<p /> <p>The information as requested is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2015-06-18T13:40:56.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350105/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350105/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-11","Prescribed Industrial Diseases","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many claims they have received for Prescribed Disease C3b in the last 10 years; and of these, how many were allowed.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350106","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-18","<p /> <p>The 1991 Health and Safety Executive (HSE) report presented the findings of a 1990 survey of sheep dipping and was published by HSE as an internal document in May 1991.</p><p> </p><p>The report was discussed at a meeting of the then Health and Safety Commission’s Agricultural Industry Advisory Committee (AIAC) working group, Chemicals In Agriculture (ChemAg), on 10 July 1991. The ChemAg working group membership included HSE, the Confederation of British Industry, the Trades Union Congress and other industry organisations.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2015-06-18T13:32:17.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350106/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350106/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-11","Sheep Dipping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the statement by George Eustice, Minister of State, Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on 10 June (HC Deb, col 136WH), who published the 1991 Health and Safety Executive report of an inquiry into sheep dipping; and to whom it was distributed.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350107","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-24","<p>According to latest reports from The Border Consortium (TBC) at the end of December there were 110,094 refugees who had been verified in the TBC database and were living in the camps. According to UNHCR’s refugees profiling report on years of residency, as of 2014: approximately 64% of the refugees have lived in the shelter for less than 10 years. Almost 30% have lived in the shelter between 11-20 years and only 7% have lived in the shelter over 20 years.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-06-24T15:26:20.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350107/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350107/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-11","Burma: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Verma on 10 June (HL125), what is their current estimate of the number of men, women and children in those camps; why that estimate was not given in that Answer; and what is their estimate of the average number of years refugees have been living in the camps on the Burma–Thai border.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350108","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-22","<p>The conference was a multilateral event hosted by the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation and not by Saudi Arabia, and therefore was not an appropriate forum to discuss individual Saudi Arabian legal cases. However, we are extremely concerned about Raif Badawi’s case and have discussed it at the most senior levels in the Government of Saudi Arabia, most recently on 9 June. We await the outcome of the current Saudi Arabian Supreme Court review of the case.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-22T11:25:21.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350108/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350108/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-11","Raif Badawi","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they pressed for the case of Raif Badawi to be discussed at the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation Conference in Jeddah on 3 and 4 June; and if so, what was the response of the government of Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350109","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>NHS England collects the number of operations cancelled at the ‘last minute’ for non-clinical reasons on a quarterly basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of cancelled elective operations in the final quarter of 2013-14 was not the highest ever recorded. The highest number of cancelled elective operations was recorded in quarter 4 2000-01.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Cancelled elective operations as a percentage of elective admissions are stable. In both 2009-10 and 2013-14 cancelled elective operations represented 0.9% of elective admissions, despite a 546,000 increase in the number of elective admissions in this period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Health Service should do everything it can to reduce cancellations and keep them to an absolute minimum. Where this is unavoidable, patients should receive treatment as soon as possible. This is reinforced by a pledge in the NHS Constitution for all patients who have operations cancelled, on or after the day of admission (including the day of surgery), for non-clinical reasons to be offered another binding date within 28 days, or the patient’s treatment to be funded at the time and hospital of the patient’s choice.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-06-19T10:58:30.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350109/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","Surgery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the number of cancelled operations in the National Health Service in the final quarter of 2013–14 was the highest ever recorded.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350110","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>NHS England collects the number of operations cancelled at the ‘last minute’ for non-clinical reasons on a quarterly basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of cancelled elective operations in the final quarter of 2013-14 was not the highest ever recorded. The highest number of cancelled elective operations was recorded in quarter 4 2000-01.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Cancelled elective operations as a percentage of elective admissions are stable. In both 2009-10 and 2013-14 cancelled elective operations represented 0.9% of elective admissions, despite a 546,000 increase in the number of elective admissions in this period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Health Service should do everything it can to reduce cancellations and keep them to an absolute minimum. Where this is unavoidable, patients should receive treatment as soon as possible. This is reinforced by a pledge in the NHS Constitution for all patients who have operations cancelled, on or after the day of admission (including the day of surgery), for non-clinical reasons to be offered another binding date within 28 days, or the patient’s treatment to be funded at the time and hospital of the patient’s choice.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL425","2015-06-19T12:27:02.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350110/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/350110/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-11","Surgery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to reduce the number of cancelled operations in the National Health Service.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL424"
