e Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349574/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Cancer: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions Ministers in his Department have had with Public Health England on the types of cancers that it will include in potential local pilot tests within the Be Clear on Cancer programme; and whether it is proposed that cervical cancer will be included in that programme.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","1998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349575","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-23","<p>Attitude is Everything's Charter of Best Practice is a positive contribution to improving deaf and disabled people’s access to, and enjoyment of, live music. It is essential that cultural events are accessible to everyone, so it is encouraging to hear that over 90 venues have signed up to the Charter.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-23T15:50:40.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349575/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349575/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-10","Music","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policies of Attitude is Everything's Charter of Best Practice for live music events.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","2069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349576","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>I most recently discussed Iran's nuclear programme, among other issues, with the Israeli National Security Adviser during his visit on 3-4 June. Officials from the Government of Israel also have regular discussions with our Embassy in Tel Aviv about Iran and the E3+3 negotiations with Iran on its nuclear programme.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:27:40.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349576/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349576/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Israeli counterpart on Iran's nuclear programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","1905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349577","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>We are aware of media reports that nuclear experts from the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK) visited Iran this year. If true, these reports are very concerning. We continue to monitor any evidence of nuclear cooperation between these two states, and to support and lead international efforts to prevent the proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction, including the spread of related knowledge and technology.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:39:07.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349577/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349577/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on North Korean nuclear experts visiting Tehran.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","1906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349578","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","Ministers and FCO officials regularly engage their counterparts in the Gulf on Iran. This includes discussions of the nuclear negotiations, nuclear-related sanctions and Iran's nuclear programme. We remain committed to reaching a comprehensive agreement on Iran's nuclear programme which will be in the interest of the region and the rest of the world.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:22:23.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349578/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349578/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in the Gulf on Iran's nuclear programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","1908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349579","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-15","<p>I expect to bring forward proposals to establish a Joint Committee on Restoration and Renewal before the House rises for the summer recess.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2015-06-15T15:48:07.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349579/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349579/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-10","Palace of Westminster: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if he will bring forward proposals to establish a Joint Committee on Restoration and Renewal of the Palace of Westminster.","false","Biography information for Lord Haselhurst","Saffron Walden","Sir Alan Haselhurst","1790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349580","Home Office","false","2015-06-17","<p>The intelligence agencies’ work is carried out in accordance with a strict legal and policy framework that ensures their activities are authorised, necessary and proportionate, and provides for rigorous oversight. Intelligence activity is overseen by Secretaries of State, independent Interception of Communications and Intelligence Services Commissioners, the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament, and held to account by the independent Investigatory Powers Tribunal.</p><p>Since 2010, the Government has taken a range of measures to strengthen this oversight and increase transparency about security and intelligence matters where this does not damage national security. Oversight was significantly enhanced through the Justice and Security Act 2013, which expanded the remit and powers of the ISC. The Government has provided extra resources to the Commissioners who oversee the use of intrusive powers by the intelligence agencies, put elements of oversight on a more transparent and, where possible, statutory footing. In addition, the Interception of Communications Commissioner now produces six monthly rather than annual reports.</p><p>The Government is taking full account of David Anderson QC’s report and will give full consideration to his detailed recommendations, and those made by the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament, when considering if further imrpovements to the oversight system are needed.</p><p>The Security and Intelligence Agencies are subject to close budgetary scrutiny and challenging efficiency targets. Their accounts are audited by the National Audit Office. National Audit Office staff have access to relevant records for this purpose. The expenditure and resource allocations of the intelligence agencies are also scrutinised by the ISC as part of its remit.</p><p>National Security matters are a reserved issue ( this is called “excepted” in Northern Ireland) and have not been devolved. The actions of the Security Service within a devolved region are subject to the same high standards of oversight regardless of where they are operating geographically.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","2060 ; 2062","2015-06-17T13:53:16.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349580/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349580/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-10","Intelligence Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to make the Security Service more transparent and accountable.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349581","Home Office","false","2015-06-17","<p>The intelligence agencies’ work is carried out in accordance with a strict legal and policy framework that ensures their activities are authorised, necessary and proportionate, and provides for rigorous oversight. Intelligence activity is overseen by Secretaries of State, independent Interception of Communications and Intelligence Services Commissioners, the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament, and held to account by the independent Investigatory Powers Tribunal.</p><p>Since 2010, the Government has taken a range of measures to strengthen this oversight and increase transparency about security and intelligence matters where this does not damage national security. Oversight was significantly enhanced through the Justice and Security Act 2013, which expanded the remit and powers of the ISC. The Government has provided extra resources to the Commissioners who oversee the use of intrusive powers by the intelligence agencies, put elements of oversight on a more transparent and, where possible, statutory footing. In addition, the Interception of Communications Commissioner now produces six monthly rather than annual reports.</p><p>The Government is taking full account of David Anderson QC’s report and will give full consideration to his detailed recommendations, and those made by the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament, when considering if further imrpovements to the oversight system are needed.</p><p>The Security and Intelligence Agencies are subject to close budgetary scrutiny and challenging efficiency targets. Their accounts are audited by the National Audit Office. National Audit Office staff have access to relevant records for this purpose. The expenditure and resource allocations of the intelligence agencies are also scrutinised by the ISC as part of its remit.</p><p>National Security matters are a reserved issue ( this is called “excepted” in Northern Ireland) and have not been devolved. The actions of the Security Service within a devolved region are subject to the same high standards of oversight regardless of where they are operating geographically.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","2060 ; 2061","2015-06-17T13:53:17.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349581/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349581/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-10","Intelligence Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to ensure the Security Service is properly audited.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349582","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) continues to make progress in improving procurement, as evidenced in the latest National Audit Office Major Projects Report, which recorded the best cost performance on major MOD projects since 2005 and the best time performance since at least 2001. Our 10-year, affordable and realistic equipment and support plan, which now underpins defence procurement, is also having a positive effect on the way we buy and support equipment for the Armed Forces.</p><p>Defence Equipment and Support (DE&amp;S), where most equipment procurement is undertaken, was established in April 2014 as a bespoke trading entity - an Arm's Length Body of the MOD. The changed status of DE&amp;S, and its associated management freedoms, marked the beginning of a three-year timeline to transform it into a best-in-class defence acquisition and support organisation. Through this programme, DE&amp;S will draw on industry best practice to review and improve project controls and programme management, thereby enabling the organisation to operate in a more business-like fashion.</p><p>The MOD also continues to work with suppliers to ensure defence procurement represents value for money, while ensuring that suppliers are paid a fair and reasonable price. For example, the new Single Source Procurement Reform Framework, known as the Orange Book, requires suppliers to provide regular, standardised reports on single source contracts, and comply with new costing regulations, as set out in the Defence Reform Act 2014 and the Single Source Contract Regulations 2014.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-18T15:42:04.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349582/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349582/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what continuous improvement programme there is for his Department's procurement practices.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349583","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-19","<p>The Ministry of Defence has no plans to examine the unification of basic training across the three Services.</p><p>The three Services have unique identities and make unique contributions to Defence which are reflected in their distinctive approaches to training. However, where possible, Defence strives to identify and assess opportunities for joint training efficiencies while still fulfilling individual Service requirements; the Defence Technical Training Change Programme is a good example of a collaborative effort that is seeking to make efficiencies from previously separate single Service technical training activities, managed by a single Defence College for Technical Training.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-19T13:06:55.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349583/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349583/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will examine the potential savings from unifying basic training for all armed services.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349584","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-19","<p>On 1 April 2010, the average size of an Infantry battalion was 570; the equivalent figure for 1 April 2015 was 530. These figures reflect a reduction in the average size of an Infantry battalion under Army 2020. The figures have been rounded to the nearest 10 and reflect only those Infantry personnel in an Infantry battalion, not any attached personnel from other areas of the Army.</p><p>On 1 April 2010, the average size of an Infantry battalion was 570; the equivalent figure for 1 April 2015 was 530. These figures reflect a reduction in the average size of an Infantry battalion under Army 2020. The figures have been rounded to the nearest 10 and reflect only those Infantry personnel in an Infantry battalion, not any attached personnel from other areas of the Army.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-19T13:03:47.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349584/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349584/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Army: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average size of an infantry battalion (a) was in 2010 and (b) is now.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349585","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-15","<p>The most senior serving Army Officer in Northern Ireland is Brigadier Ralph William Wooddisse MBE MC, Commander 38 (Irish) Brigade. He reports to Major General Giles Hill CBE, General Officer Commanding 1 (UK) Division.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-15T15:45:22.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349585/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349585/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Army: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, who the most senior serving army officer is in Northern Ireland; and to whom he or she reports.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349586","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-18","<p>The UK and EU Member States have agreed to establish a military Common Security and Defence Policy (CSDP) operation to disrupt trafficking and smuggling networks in the Mediterranean, which will include migrant flows from Libya ports. To stop the flows reaching Libya in the first place we are engaging with source and transit countries to address the causes of migrants leaving their home countries, through development aid, humanitarian support, addressing human rights abuses and tackling conflict.</p><p>We are also working to bring order and stability in Libya to make it a more difficult operating environment for smugglers and traffickers. Only a stable and representative Government of National Accord (GNA) can deal with the political and security challenges Libya faces, including the control of her borders.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-06-18T14:47:52.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349586/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349586/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to reduce the flow of migrants from ports in Libya.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2059"
