eland) and have not been devolved. The actions of the Security Service within a devolved region are subject to the same high standards of oversight regardless of where they are operating geographically.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","2061 ; 2062","2015-06-17T13:53:16.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349587/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349587/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-10","Intelligence Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what provisions there are for oversight of the activities of the Security Service in the devolved assemblies of the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349588","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-19","<p>The single Services routinely consider synergies in their training programmes. The Defence Academy in Shrivenham is an example of where joint-service training creates efficiencies for the Defence budget. However, the British Army and Royal Marines have distinct and specific roles, and the training received by their officers recognises this.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-19T13:07:51.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349588/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349588/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will assess the value for money to the Army of adopting the officer training procedures of the Royal Marines.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349589","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-19","<p>There are no plans to integrate the Parachute Regiment into the RAF and as the hon. Member will be aware, in line with long held Government policy, we do not comment on matters to do with Special Forces.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-19T13:06:23.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349589/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349589/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Air Force","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will integrate the Parachute Regiment and the SAS into the RAF.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349590","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Government takes its responsibilities for maintaining a credible nuclear deterrent extremely seriously and continually conducts assessments to ensure that the credibility and standards for safety, security and operational effectiveness are met. It would not be appropriate to comment on any further details as this could allow conclusions to be drawn on the UK's capabilities.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-17T16:20:17.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349590/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349590/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that the UK's nuclear capabilities are sufficient to meet the deterrence requirements.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349591","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-17","<p>It is unclear what the hon. Member is proposing. Specific areas of the Armed Forces are already subject to independent assessment by relevant inspectorates, including Ofsted and Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Constabularies.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-17T16:19:50.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349591/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349591/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Reserve Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will establish an independent civilian armed forces inspectorate.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349592","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-15","<p>The safety of submarines and other vessels is paramount, and since 1993 the Royal Navy (RN) has adhered to &quot;The Code of Practice for the Conduct of Submarine Operations in the Vicinity of Fishing Vessels&quot;. This was agreed by the Fishing Industry Safety Group, and is a focus for submarine crews.</p><p>To support the code there are regular consultation meetings between the RN and fishermen's associations in the Clyde, West Coast of Scotland, Irish Sea and the Portland/Plymouth regions.</p><p>In addition the RN has a Fishery Liaison Officer to provide a central point of contact with the UK fishing industry.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-15T15:46:03.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349592/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349592/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that UK submarines are not a danger to fishing boats.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349593","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-16","<p>There are no restrictions on a Royal Marine Officer becoming Chief of the Defence Staff.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-16T15:15:31.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349593/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349593/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Chiefs of Staff: Marines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that a Royal Marine officer can become Chief of the Defence Staff.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349594","Department of Health","false","2015-06-18","<p>The use of innovative T-cell therapies, including CAR-T cells, to treat specific forms of leukaemia is a rapidly developing field. Clinical trials have shown that CAR-T cell therapy has been effective in treating small numbers of patients where other forms of treatment have failed to be effective. The Department will maintain close dialogue with key medical groups as this technology develops.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-18T16:09:58.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349594/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349594/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Leukaemia: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will discuss with the British Medical Association and other medical bodies the treatment of leukemia with T-cells.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","1793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349595","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-19","<p>The requested breakdown by rank of trained UK Regular Officers and Warrant Officers based at each officer training establishment, as at 1 April 2015, is provided in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>NATO Rank</strong></td><td><strong>Britannia Royal Naval College (Dartmouth)</strong></td><td><strong>Commando Training Centre Royal Marines (Lympstone)</strong></td><td><strong>Royal Military Academy (Sandhurst) </strong></td><td><strong>Royal Air Force College (Cranwell) </strong></td></tr><tr><td>OF-7</td><td>-</td><td>~</td><td>~</td><td>-</td></tr><tr><td>OF-6</td><td>-</td><td>-</td><td>~</td><td>-</td></tr><tr><td>OF-5</td><td>~</td><td>~</td><td>~</td><td>~</td></tr><tr><td>OF-4</td><td>10</td><td>10</td><td>10</td><td>10</td></tr><tr><td>OF-3</td><td>10</td><td>30</td><td>40</td><td>30</td></tr><tr><td>OF-2</td><td>30</td><td>40</td><td>50</td><td>90</td></tr><tr><td>OF-1</td><td>-</td><td>20</td><td>~</td><td>~</td></tr><tr><td>OR-9</td><td>10</td><td>20</td><td>10</td><td>30</td></tr><tr><td>OR-8</td><td>-</td><td>40</td><td>30</td><td>-</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note: Figures are rounded and may not equal the sums of their rounded parts. When rounding to the nearest 10, numbers ending in 5 have been rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias. &quot;~&quot; denotes fewer than 5 and “-” denotes zero. Trained UK Regular Forces does not include Gurkhas, full-time reserve personnel and mobilised reservists. NATO Rank Codes equivalence in UK Service Rank (Army) is as follows: OF-7 Major General; OF-6 Brigadier; OF-5 Colonel; OF-4 Lieutenant Colonel; OF-3 Major; OF-2 Captain; OF-1 Lieutenant/2nd Lieutenant; OR-9 Warrant Officer Class-1; OR-8 Warrant Officer Class-2.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-19T13:04:34.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349595/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349595/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) officers and (b) warrant officers of each rank are based at each officer training establishment.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349596","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-17","<p>International defence training is an important part of our international defence engagement strategy, which seeks to use our national capabilities to extend the influence of the UK in the world.</p><p> </p><p>The table below sets out the figures for UK-funded students undertaking initial officer training:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Financial Year </strong></td><td><strong>Britannia Royal Naval College (Dartmouth) £000 </strong></td><td><strong>Commando Training Centre Royal Marines (Lympstone) £000</strong></td><td><strong>Royal Military Academy (Sandhurst) £000 </strong></td><td><strong>Royal Air Force College (Cranwell) £000</strong></td></tr><tr><td>2010-11</td><td>520</td><td>0</td><td>1,383</td><td>178</td></tr><tr><td>2011-12</td><td>378</td><td>60</td><td>1,565</td><td>232</td></tr><tr><td>2012-13</td><td>868</td><td>118</td><td>1,984</td><td>312</td></tr><tr><td>2013-14</td><td>986</td><td>118</td><td>2,145</td><td>394</td></tr><tr><td>2014-15</td><td>990</td><td>0</td><td>2,416</td><td>550</td></tr></tbody></table>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-17T16:24:19.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349596/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349596/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the costs of training cadets from outside the UK have been at each officer training establishment in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349597","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not have a valuation for the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst.</p><p>However, as and when a site is declared surplus, a valuation is obtained. This is not released as to do so would prejudice the market.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-17T16:23:15.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349597/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349597/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Royal Military Academy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the value is of the estate of HMA Sandhurst.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349598","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>We and other members of the Board of Governors of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) receive quarterly reports on Iran's nuclear programme, the IAEA's efforts to address the Possible Military Dimensions of Iran’s nuclear programme, and the nuclear aspects of the Joint Plan of Action with the E3+3.</p><p>The IAEA Director General issued his latest report on the status of Iran’s nuclear programme on 29 May 2015; this confirms Iran continues to implement its commitments under the Joint Plan of Action. However, we remain disappointed by Iran’s limited engagement with the IAEA on Possible Military Dimensions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:48:29.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349598/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349598/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of Iran's level of co-operation with International Atomic Energy Agency investigations into its current and previous nuclear activities.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","2010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349599","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>We are aware of recent media reports of the Supreme Leader’s comments. A comprehensive nuclear deal with Iran that addresses our proliferation concerns will need to be fully verifiable by the International Atomic Energy Agency. This must include robust monitoring of Iran’s nuclear activities, and its implementation of the Additional Protocol, in order to reassure the international community that Iran’s nuclear programme is exclusively peaceful.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:45:00.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349599/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349599/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on recent comments by Ayatollah Ali Khamenei that the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) would be denied access to Iran's military facilities and nuclear officials under a nuclear deal; and what assessment he has made of the effect such a stance by Iran would have in the IAEA's ability to verify that country's adherence to a permanent nuclear deal.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","2008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349600","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has monthly access to the reactor at Arak. The IAEA Director General’s 29 May Iran report confirms that Iran continues to abide by its commitments under the Joint Plan of Action. Access for the IAEA to Parchin remains an important but unfulfilled step. The Director General’s report reiterates that clean-up activities at the site are likely to have undermined the Agency’s ability to conduct effective verification, however it is imperative that Iran provides swift access as the Agency continues to request. We fully support their work on this crucial issue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:46:39.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349600/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349600/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on whether Iran has denied International Atomic Energy inspectors access to its Arak and Parchin facilities.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","2009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349601","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-15","<p>I cannot provide an exact start date for construction. However, as stated in Highways England Delivery Plan 2015-2020, construction of the A1(M) Junction 6-8 smart motorway scheme in Hertfordshire is planned to start construction in late in the 2019/20, and complete approximately 12 months later.</p><p> </p><p>The next step is the detailed design and planning of the scheme, plus consultation with the local community to produce the best possible scheme. That work will be taken forward by Highways England and is expected to start shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-15T11:26:16.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349601/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349601/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-10","A1(M): Hertfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for the widening of the A1(M) in Hertfordshire.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","2065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349602","Department for Education","false","2015-06-15","<p>At a time of difficult financial decisions for the country, we have made a conscious choice to prioritise spending on education. We will continue to protect the schools budget, and will ensure that the funding schools receive increases as pupil numbers increase. In 2015-16, we added £390million to the budgets of 69 local authorities considered to have been unfairly funded in previous years, including £11.3million of additional funding for Hertfordshire.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-15T16:23:34.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349602/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349602/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-10","Schools: Hertfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if the Government will take steps to maintain the schools budget and per-pupil spending in Hertfordshire.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","2066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349603","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-15","<p>Department for Business, Innovation and Skills Ministers’ are engaging actively with our EU counterparts on the EU’s trade agenda. Most recently, the Minister of State for Trade and Investment attended the OECD’s Ministerial meeting on Trade, Investment and Development where he discussed the full range of EU trade negotiations with EU Trade Ministers, including those of France, Germany, Spain and Portugal. The Minister of State also discussed relevant negotiations with Trade Ministers from several non-EU countries at this meeting, including China.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-15T16:34:42.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349603/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349603/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-10","EU External Trade: Asia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in other EU member states on negotiating a trade deal between the EU and (a) China and (b) India.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","1785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349604","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-15","<p>Information in the form requested is not readily available and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-15T15:42:21.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349604/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349604/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Russia: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many British diplomats have been withdrawn or expelled from Russia in each of the last 20 years; and what the explanation was for each such withdrawal or expulsion.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","1786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349605","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-15","<p>I can confirm that there have been no unauthorised incursions by Russian air forces into UK sovereign airspace within the last 10 years.</p><p>For information on the number of Russian naval incursions into UK territorial waters I refer the hon. Member to the answer given on 24 March 2015 by the previous Minister of State for the Armed Forces (Mark Francois) to Question number 218391.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence does not hold or have access to information on Russian incursions into NATO Allies territories.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-06-15T16:01:57.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349605/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349605/answer","20150324_Hansard_extract_on_Territorial_Waters.doc","20150324_Hansard_extract_on_Territorial_Waters.doc","20150324 - Hansard extract on Territorial Waters","20150324 - Hansard extract on Territorial Waters","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349605/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-10","Russia: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many unauthorised incursions Russian (a) naval and (b) air forces made into (i) UK and (ii) NATO Allies' territory in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","1788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349606","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-15","<p>Information in the form requested is not readily available and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-15T15:43:28.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349606/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349606/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Russia: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many Russian diplomats have been expelled or withdrawn in each of the last 20 years; and for what reason each such expulsion or withdrawal occurred.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","1813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349607","Prime Minister","false","2015-06-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave it him on 9 June 2015, UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-04/1272/" target="_blank">1272</a>.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-06-15T15:37:21.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349607/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349607/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-06-10","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what information he holds on work undertaken or progress made by the Chilcot Inquiry since January 2015; whether that inquiry (a) has received or (b) will receive public funds in respect of the period from January to June 2015; and when he next plans to next update the House on progress with that inquiry.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","1812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349608","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-15","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has not sold tax credit debt. It has contracted out collection, but retains ownership.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-15T16:56:19.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349608/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349608/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-10","Working Tax Credit: Overpayments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2015 to Question 576, whether HM Revenue and Customs (a) sold working tax credit debt to external debt collection agencies and (b) contracted out the collection of working tax credit debt while retaining ownership.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","1830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349609","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-17","<p>Although a number of measures have been introduced to prevent the occurrence of tax credits overpayments - and we will continue to consider further measures - we expect that tax credits related debt will continue to rise as we move towards it being replaced by Universal Credit due to the design of the tax credits system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The tax credits system is an annual system – all awards and payments are “provisional” until finalised after the end of the year, once income and family circumstances are confirmed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Tax credits are responsive to changes in claimants’ circumstances: overpayments – as well as underpayments – typically occur because people do not report changes promptly. However, due to the annual nature of the tax credits system, with tax credits awards being based on household income for a tax year, overpayments can occur even when the claimant and HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) do everything right. Where error and fraud is identified, overpayments are generated.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-17T16:23:48.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349609/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349609/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-10","Working Tax Credit: Overpayments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2015 to Question 578, for what reasons a temporary rise in tax credit related debt was forecast to take place before the replacement of tax credits by universal credit.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","1831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349610","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-16","<p>A wide range of HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and HM Treasury financial, debt recovery and analysis experts were involved in planning the use of debt collection agencies for tax credit debt as part.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The management of conflicts of interest for Civil Servants is set out in the Civil Service Code and the Civil Service Management Code.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-16T15:52:40.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349610/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349610/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-10","Working Tax Credit: Overpayments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2015 to Question 579, which experts were involved in the planning process for outsourcing working tax credit debt collection to the private sector; whether any of those experts had a financial interest in the debt collection sector; whether those experts advised HM Revenue and Customs to proceed with the use of private sector debt collection agencies; and whether advice from those experts was provided orally or in writing.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","1832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349611","Department of Health","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Health and Care Professions Council (HCPC) is a self-financing, independent regulator that is accountable to Parliament through the Professional Standards Authority whose role is to assess the HCPC’s performance, conduct audits, scrutinise their decisions and report to Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The professional regulators are funded by registrant fees and as independent bodies it is for them to set their fees at a level which ensures they can fulfil their statutory role of protecting, promoting and maintaining the health and safety of the public.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of the process for raising fees the HCPC undertook a public consultation, the responses from which were considered by the HCPC before implementing the fee rise.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-17T10:31:36.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349611/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349611/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Health and Care Professions Council: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for health professionals of the decision by the Health and Care Professions Council to increase its mandatory registration fee; and what information he holds on whether that Council assessed the affordability of that increase for (a) part-time and (b) other members.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","1880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349612","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-17","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has a statutory duty to maintain taxpayer confidentiality, which applies to all information the department holds in connection with its functions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-17T16:22:47.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349612/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349612/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-10","Royal Family: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 8 June 2015 to Question 956 and with reference to the 2013 Memorandum of Understanding on Royal Taxation referred to in that Answer, for what reasons his policy is to accord HM The Queen the same privacy and confidentiality in relation to her tax affairs when she pays tax on a voluntary basis, unlike other taxpayers.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","1899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349613","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-15","<p>I will bring forward proposals on English Votes for English Laws shortly. There will be time for the House to give them full consideration and there will be a full debate on them.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","1924 ; 1925 ; 1926 ; 1927","2015-06-15T16:17:30.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349613/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349613/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-10","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if he will make it his policy that a select committee of this House considers any changes to Standing Orders to create English votes for English laws before a motion is tabled for their approval.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","1923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349614","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-15","<p>I will bring forward proposals on English Votes for English Laws shortly. There will be time for the House to give them full consideration and there will be a full debate on them.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","1923 ; 1925 ; 1926 ; 1927","2015-06-15T16:17:30.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349614/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349614/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-10","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, with reference to the Implications for Devolution of England, Cm 8969, published in December 2014, whether he will use Option 3 in the paper as the basis for his proposals on English votes for English laws.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","1924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349615","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-15","<p>I will bring forward proposals on English Votes for English Laws shortly. There will be time for the House to give them full consideration and there will be a full debate on them.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","1923 ; 1924 ; 1926 ; 1927","2015-06-15T16:17:31.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349615/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349615/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-10","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, whether under his proposals for English votes for English laws, an English Grand Committee will be required to vote on a legislative consent motion before the Third Reading of any bill with England-only implications.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","1925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349616","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-15","<p>I will bring forward proposals on English Votes for English Laws shortly. There will be time for the House to give them full consideration and there will be a full debate on them.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","1923 ; 1924 ; 1925 ; 1927","2015-06-15T16:17:31.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349616/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349616/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-10","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, whether under his proposals for English votes for English laws, bills may be split so that parts of them can be considered as England-only.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","1926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349617","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-15","<p>I will bring forward proposals on English Votes for English Laws shortly. There will be time for the House to give them full consideration and there will be a full debate on them.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","1923 ; 1924 ; 1925 ; 1926","2015-06-15T16:17:30.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349617/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349617/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-10","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, whether under his proposals for English votes for English laws, the Speaker will determine whether a bill is considered by all hon. Members or by those representing English constituencies.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","1927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349618","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) Director General in his 29 May report on the status of Iran’s nuclear programme reiterated concerns about the possible existence in Iran of undisclosed nuclear-related activities involving military organisations. We are disappointed by Iran’s limited engagement with the IAEA on this issue, and fully support the IAEA in continuing to pursue the possible military dimensions to Iran's nuclear programme.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:52:25.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349618/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349618/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of possible military dimensions to Iran's nuclear programme.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349619","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The E3+3 and Iran agreed in Lausanne on 2 April that a robust and credible regime for monitoring of the provisions of a comprehensive agreement would be put in place, including implementation of the modified code 3.1 and the Additional Protocol. A comprehensive nuclear deal with Iran that addresses our proliferation concerns will need to be fully verifiable by the International Atomic Energy Agency in order to reassure the international community that Iran’s nuclear programme is exclusively peaceful.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:54:07.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349619/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349619/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the proposed verification mechanism to monitor Iran's nuclear programme in a permanent nuclear agreement.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349620","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The E3+3 and Iran agreed in Lausanne on 2 April that Iran would implement its Additional Protocol under a comprehensive deal. Iran’s implementation of its Additional Protocol will be an important element of a robust and credible verification regime that enables the International Atomic Energy Agency to confirm that Iran is abiding by its nuclear commitments under a comprehensive agreement.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-16T13:55:26.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349620/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349620/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of Iran's willingness to agree, implement and adhere to the Additional Protocol as part of an agreement on its nuclear programme.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349621","Department of Health","false","2015-06-15","<p>A number of immunotherapy drugs are licensed for the treatment of different cancers and are available for use on the National Health Service, subject to funding decisions by the relevant commissioner. Pembrolizumab and nivolumab are two new immunotherapies that are able to treat a number of cancers. The first cancer where these medicines have shown significant increase in patient survival is advanced stage of melanoma. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency has issued early access scientific opinions for both products for treatment of advanced stage melanoma. The Early Access to Medicines scientific opinion for pembrolizumab (Merck Sharp &amp; Dohme) was issued in March 2015 and that for nivolumab (Bristol Myers Squibb) in May 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Applications for marketing authorisations for both products have already received positive opinions from the European Medicines Agency and marketing authorisations are anticipated to be issued by the European Commission soon.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Through its technology appraisal programme, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has been able to recommend a number of immunotherapy treatments including, ipilimumab and obinutuzumab. NICE is currently developing technology appraisal guidance on other immunotherapy treatments including nivolumab and pembrolizumab. Wherever possible, NICE aims to publish draft or final guidance on drugs referred to it within a few months of the drug receiving a license. NHS commissioners are legally required to fund drugs and treatments recommended in NICE technology appraisal guidance.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-15T13:53:37.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349621/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349621/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Cancer: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to expedite the provision through the NHS of immunotherapy treatments for cancer; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","1825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349622","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-15","<p>Nigeria’s new President Muhammadu Buhari was inaugurated on 29 May. He has not yet appointed any Ministers. We regularly engage with Nigerian politicians and officials on security and the fight against terrorism, particularly the threat posed by Boko Haram. The Prime Minister discussed this when he met President Buhari on 23 May and the Foreign Secretary raised the matter again when he met President Buhari on 29 May, at his inauguration in Abuja, Nigeria.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2015-06-15T13:28:46.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349622/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349622/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Nigeria: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with (a) his Nigerian counterpart and (b) the President of Nigeria on suicide bomb attacks in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","1826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349623","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-18","<p>On 1 June 2015 the Chancellor extended the successful trading plan, which will continue to dispose of Lloyds shares into the market until no later than 31 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has also announced that a sale to include retail investors will take place within the next twelve months</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-18T11:11:17.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349623/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349623/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-10","Lloyds Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects the next tranche of the share sale of Lloyds Bank to take place; and what steps he plans to take to ensure the widest share ownership.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","1827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349624","Department of Health","false","2015-06-15","<p>NHS England has not made an independent assessment of the accuracy and effectiveness of Body Mass Index (BMI) in determining overweight and obesity in adults.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England and NHS England support the implementation of expert guidance on the use of BMI provided by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Currently, NICE recommends that BMI is used routinely by healthcare professionals to assess obesity in adults and children.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NICE recommends the use of additional validated obesity measures, such as waist circumference, to be undertaken alongside BMI when assessing overweight and obesity in individuals to give more detailed assessment of an individual’s health risk.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-15T11:31:49.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349624/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349624/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Obesity: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment NHS England has made of the accuracy and effectiveness of the traditional BMI test in determining levels of obesity in adults.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","1828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349625","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-15","<p>The Government will provide all the support necessary to the next Governor of Gibraltar, as it has to the current Governor, to enable him or her to exercise his or her responsibilities to the full and in the interests of Gibraltar and the people of Gibraltar.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-15T15:44:18.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349625/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349625/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-10","Gibraltar: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will take steps to provide additional support to the next Governor of Gibraltar in protecting the interests of the people of Gibraltar.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","1829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349627","Department for Education","false","2015-06-16","<p>The savings announced by the Chancellor will come from a variety of measures including expected departmental underspends in demand-led budgets, efficiencies and some small budgetary reductions.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-16T14:25:48.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349627/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349627/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-10","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans reductions in spending on education and training for 16 to 19 year olds in order to implement the decision announced on 4 June 2015 to reduce the funding of her Department.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","2022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349628","Attorney General","false","2015-06-18","<p>The number of full-time equivalent staff who are qualified (a) barristers and (b) solicitors who were employed by the Crown Prosecution Service in each year from 2010 to 2015 is shown in the table below</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Barristers</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Solicitors</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>740.3</p></td><td><p>2085.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>741.3</p></td><td><p>1845.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>646.8</p></td><td><p>1705.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>612.2</p></td><td><p>1617.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>627.7</p></td><td><p>1627.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes: </strong>Data extracted from the CPS HR Database iTrent as at the 31<sup>st</sup> March in each year Data may be subject to change due to retrospective changes in the HR database Data may differ from previously published data due to differing specifications</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-18T09:26:44.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349628/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349628/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-10","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many full-time equivalent staff who are qualified (a) barristers and (b) solicitors were employed by the Crown Prosecution Service in each year from 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","1930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349629","Attorney General","false","2015-06-18","<p>The number of full-time equivalent people employed on the Crown Prosecution Service’s staff in each of the years from 2010 to 2015 is shown below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FTE Staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>8,094</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>7,464</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>7,046</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>6,611</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>6,135</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-18T09:30:21.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349629/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349629/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-10","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many full-time equivalent staff were employed by the Crown Prosecution Service in each of the years from 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","1931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349630","Attorney General","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service publishes its casework statistics on a financial year basis. The number of criminal prosecutions finalised between April 2010 and March 2015 are as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Finalised Prosecutions</p></td><td><p>958,834</p></td><td><p>896,505</p></td><td><p>806,458</p></td><td><p>738,064</p></td><td><p>664,493</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-17T10:14:06.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349630/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349630/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-10","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how  many criminal prosecutions were undertaken by the Crown Prosecution Service in each of the years 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","2029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349631","Attorney General","false","2015-06-18","<p>The proportion of the budget that the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) spent on (a) premises, (b) administration, (c) staff, (d) external suppliers other than external Counsel, (e) external Counsel and (f) other costs in each of the years 2010 to 2015 is given below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Premises</strong></p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Administration</strong></p></td><td><p>3%</p></td><td><p>3%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Staff</strong></p></td><td><p>53%</p></td><td><p>56%</p></td><td><p>57%</p></td><td><p>57%</p></td><td><p>55%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>External suppliers</strong></p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Counsel</strong></p></td><td><p>19%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td><td><p>19%</p></td><td><p>21%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Other</strong></p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Note: </strong>The figures for the years 2010/11, 2011/12 and 2012/13 do not sum to 100% because in each of these years the CPS reported a small underspend against its budget.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-18T09:25:33.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349631/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349631/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-10","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what proportion of the budget of the Crown Prosecution Service was spent on (a) premises, (b) administration, (c) staff, (d) external suppliers, other than external Counsel, (e) external Counsel and (f) other costs in each of the years 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","2030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349632","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-19","<p>I wrote to government departments on 20 May, to ask them to identify savings and achieve underspends this year.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor announced on 4 June £3bn of departmental savings in 2015-16. These savings will be achieved through further efficiency savings, tighter control of budgets to drive underspends in year, and driving through asset sales</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-06-19T13:11:27.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349632/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349632/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-10","Treasury: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his Department's press release, Chancellor announces £4.5 billion of measures to bring down debt, published on 4 June 2015, whether he will publish his correspondence of 20 May 2015 with government departments.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","1852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349633","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-16","<p /> <p>The savings for 2015-16 announced on 4 June 2015 are being achieved through further efficiency savings, tighter control of budgets to drive underspends in year, and driving through asset sales.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>As part of the £4.5 billion in-year savings announced by the Chancellor, the Department for Work and Pensions committed to delivering £105m from its £6.7bn budget in 2015-16, of which £75m is from efficiency savings. Departmental productivity is regularly assessed and is published in the Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p><p>The government is getting on with the job of repairing the public finances, and to run a surplus in this Parliament. This will create the best conditions for sustainable growth.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-16T13:42:25.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349633/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349633/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-10","Department for Work and Pensions: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to HM Treasury's press release, Chancellor announces £4.5 billion of measures to bring down debt, published on 4 June 2015, what assessment he has made of the effect on productivity of delivering efficiency savings from his Department's budget.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","1963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349634","Department of Health","false","2015-06-18","<p>As part of wider Government action on deficit reduction, the Department will deliver savings of £200 million in 2015/16 from a reduction in the Local Government Public Health Grant. We will be consulting on the best way of delivering the savings that need to be made, which will take account of and mitigate any adverse impact on productivity.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-18T11:26:45.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349634/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349634/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Department of Health: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to HM Treasury's press release, Chancellor announces £4.5 billion of measures to bring down debt, published on 4 June 2015, what assessment he has made of the effect on productivity of delivering efficiency savings from his Department's budget.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","1964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349635","Department for Education","false","2015-06-18","<p>The government is continuing to improve the public finances in order to create the best conditions for sustainable growth.</p><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p><p>The savings for 2015-16 announced on 4 June 2015 are being achieved through further efficiency savings, tighter control of budgets to drive underspends in year, and through asset sales.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No savings will be made from protected schools funding.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-06-18T10:31:43.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349635/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349635/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-10","Department for Education: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to HM Treasury's press release, Chancellor announces £4.5 billion of measures to bring down debt, published on 4 June 2015, what assessment she has made of the effect on productivity of delivering efficiency savings from her Department's budget.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","1965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349636","Department of Health","false","2015-06-18","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has an on-going evaluation programme of new Lyme tests and a new research programme in conjunction with University of Liverpool. PHE and the National Health Service are committed to using a test for which reproducible validation data exists, supported by evidence in peer reviewed publications. PHE participates in the European External Quality Assurance (EQA) scheme for Lyme disease testing which provides an independent assessment of performance. EQA is a mandatory requirement for all laboratory testing in the NHS as part of best practice. New assay systems will only be introduced if they can be shown to enhance the diagnosis of Lyme disease through scientifically conducted studies.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-18T15:39:23.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349636/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349636/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Lyme Disease: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to improve the accuracy of tests for Lyme disease.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","1999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349637","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-15","<p>Seal conservation is a devolved issue so I can only respond with respect to England. Approximately 85% of the UK seal population is in Scotland and the Scottish Government has its own legislation concerning the protection of seals.</p><p>Seals in England are primarily protected by the Conservation of Seals Act 1970. Under this Act, it is an offence to take or kill common and grey seals out of season or to use certain methods to kill or take, unless permitted to do so by a licence issued under the Act.</p><p>No licences have been issued for the culling of seals in England in the last five years.</p><p>The Government has made no assessment of the number of seals killed off the English coast.</p><p>There is no evidence to suggest that the limited local control of seals permitted in England is having an adverse effect on the conservation status of the UK seal population as a whole.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","1884","2015-06-15T11:44:51.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349637/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349637/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-10","Seals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many seals are illegally slaughtered annually in British waters.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","1885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349638","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-15","<p>Seal conservation is a devolved issue so I can only respond with respect to England. Approximately 85% of the UK seal population is in Scotland and the Scottish Government has its own legislation concerning the protection of seals.</p><p /> <p>Seals in England are primarily protected by the Conservation of Seals Act 1970. Under this Act, it is an offence to take or kill common and grey seals out of season or to use certain methods to kill or take, unless permitted to do so by a licence issued under the Act.</p><p /> <p>No licences have been issued for the culling of seals in England in the last five years.</p><p /> <p>The Act also allows the Secretary of State to provide year round protection in any specified area. Such a ‘Conservation Order’ currently protects grey and common seals on the east coast of England. Given the distribution of seal populations in England, this Order has the net effect of providing year round protection for almost all common seals and the majority of grey seals in England.</p><p /> <p>Fishermen are only permitted to kill or take, without the need for a licence, to protect their fishing equipment or fish therein if the seal is in the vicinity of the equipment at that time.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","1946","2015-06-15T11:38:57.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349638/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349638/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-10","Seals: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to protect the seal population in British waters from illegal slaughter.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","1883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349639","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-15","<p>Seal conservation is a devolved issue so I can only respond with respect to England. Approximately 85% of the UK seal population is in Scotland and the Scottish Government has its own legislation concerning the protection of seals.</p><p>Seals in England are primarily protected by the Conservation of Seals Act 1970. Under this Act, it is an offence to take or kill common and grey seals out of season or to use certain methods to kill or take, unless permitted to do so by a licence issued under the Act.</p><p>No licences have been issued for the culling of seals in England in the last five years.</p><p>The Government has made no assessment of the number of seals killed off the English coast.</p><p>There is no evidence to suggest that the limited local control of seals permitted in England is having an adverse effect on the conservation status of the UK seal population as a whole.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","1885","2015-06-15T11:44:51.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349639/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349639/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-10","Seals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many seals are slaughtered annually in British waters.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","1884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349640","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-17","<p>I am proud of the leadership role that the UK has played on tackling violence against women and children world-wide, and it will continue to be a key priority for my Department. We have increased programmes that tackle violence against women and girls by over 60% in the past two years, and now support 103 programmes in 29 countries.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID works to prevent and respond to violence against children across a wide range of humanitarian and development programmes, from our flagship £35 million investment in ending female genital mutilation, to our support to the No Lost Generation Initiative, through which the UK is funding education and psychosocial support for Syrian children to protect them from violence, abuse and exploitation.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening","1941","2015-06-17T09:38:43.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349640/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349640/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-10","Developing Countries: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to reduce violence against women in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","1940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349641","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-17","<p>I am proud of the leadership role that the UK has played on tackling violence against women and children world-wide, and it will continue to be a key priority for my Department. We have increased programmes that tackle violence against women and girls by over 60% in the past two years, and now support 103 programmes in 29 countries.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID works to prevent and respond to violence against children across a wide range of humanitarian and development programmes, from our flagship £35 million investment in ending female genital mutilation, to our support to the No Lost Generation Initiative, through which the UK is funding education and psychosocial support for Syrian children to protect them from violence, abuse and exploitation.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening","1940","2015-06-17T09:38:43.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349641/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349641/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-10","Developing Countries: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to reduce violence against children in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","1941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349642","Department of Health","false","2015-06-18","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) clinical guideline <em>Rheumatoid arthritis: The management of rheumatoid arthritis in adults</em>, published in 2009, emphasises the need for early diagnosis, with urgent referral to a specialist rheumatologist on suspicion of rheumatoid arthritis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NICE also published a quality standard on rheumatoid arthritis in June 2013. Quality standards are concise sets of prioritised statements designed to drive measurable quality improvements within a particular area of health or care. The standard makes seven statements which are indicators of good care. This includes a statement on referral that sets out that people with suspected rheumatoid arthritis are referred to a rheumatology service within three working days of presentation. It also includes a statement on assessment which recommends that people with suspected rheumatoid arthritis are assessed in a rheumatology service within three weeks of referral.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In March this year Public Health England and the Department ran a local pilot campaign to raise awareness of rheumatoid arthritis symptoms in Nottingham City and Hardwick Clinical Commissioning Groups. The aim of the campaign was to support earlier diagnosis and treatment to improve the quality of life for people with rheumatoid arthritis and an assessment is being made of its effectiveness.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-18T15:36:28.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349642/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349642/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-10","Arthritis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve the diagnosis and treatment of rheumatoid arthritis.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","1943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349643","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-16","<p>The Department issued revised speed limit guidance in January 2013 aimed mainly at local authorities who are responsible for setting speed limits on local roads where local needs and conditions suggest a speed limit which is lower than the national speed limit. It has been designed to help explain to everyone why and how local speed limits are determined. This circular has been revised following full public consultation in Summer 2012 and can be found online on GOV.UK</p><p> </p><p>THINK! launched a new campaign in October 2014 to warn drivers of the dangers of country roads. Details of the campaign can also be found on GOV.UK</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-16T14:16:32.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349643/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349643/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-10","Roads: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to reduce road accidents on rural roads.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","1942"
